# STRATEGICLAND — Atmosphere System

> Atmosphere is the **air in the room**.
> When the audience can see it but can't name it, it's working.
> When it shouts, it's broken.

---

## 1. Atmospheric Philosophy

- The page must feel **inhabited**, not rendered. Every viewport carries faint texture, light, and depth.
- Atmosphere lives in the **ambient layer** (background-most z-index). It never competes with content.
- Atmosphere is **always in motion**, but always at glacial pacing. Stillness with subtle drift = aliveness.
- Atmosphere differs by **chapter** (see `chapter-architecture.mdc`). Each chapter has its own air.

---

## 2. Grain System

Grain is the project's **fingerprint**. Every viewport has it. Always.

### 2.1 Source
- Pre-baked grain texture: `public/textures/grain-512.png` (512×512 tileable, 8-bit grayscale, organic noise, ≤ 24 KB).
- For higher fidelity scenes (hero, full-bleed images): `grain-1024.png`.
- Forbidden: pure CSS `noise()` or random per-pixel JS — too computational and visually digital.

### 2.2 Implementation
Two acceptable techniques:

**A. CSS overlay (default, lightweight)**
```css
.atmosphere-grain::after {
  content: "";
  position: absolute; inset: 0;
  background-image: url("/textures/grain-512.png");
  background-size: 256px 256px;
  background-repeat: repeat;
  mix-blend-mode: overlay;
  opacity: var(--grain-opacity, 0.06);
  pointer-events: none;
  z-index: 1;
}
```

**B. WebGL shader overlay** (only when WebGL scene is already mounted):
- Sample grain in fragment shader, animate `uTime` for slow drift.
- See `webgl-system.mdc` for shader budget.

### 2.3 Opacity ranges
| Context                 | Opacity   |
|-------------------------|-----------|
| Light scenes (warm cream backgrounds) | 0.04–0.06 |
| Dark scenes (deep black/charcoal)     | 0.08–0.12 |
| Hero / chapter establishing           | 0.10–0.14 |
| Image overlays                        | 0.05–0.08 |
| Reduced-motion mode                   | 0.04 (static, no animation) |

### 2.4 Motion
- Grain may "drift" via slow `transform: translate3d()` animation (≤ 16px range, ≥ 8s loop, `EASE.breath`).
- Or via shader UV scroll (shader-based scenes only).
- Never animate grain opacity (causes flicker).

### 2.5 Forbidden
- ❌ Coarse digital noise (looks like JPEG artifacts).
- ❌ Color grain (grain is **always** grayscale; color grading happens via blend mode).
- ❌ Animated grain at fast frequencies (>2 Hz visible change). Grain breathes, doesn't shimmer.
- ❌ Grain on interactive elements (buttons, inputs) — only on ambient and image surfaces.

---

## 3. Blur System

Blur is **focus, depth, and atmosphere**. Not decoration.

### 3.1 Blur tokens
```ts
export const BLUR = {
  whisper: "blur(2px)",   // text reveal entry, near-imperceptible
  soft:    "blur(8px)",   // image reveal entry, hover-out
  haze:    "blur(20px)",  // background imagery, ambient depth
  veil:    "blur(40px)",  // chapter transitions, dissolves
  fog:     "blur(80px)",  // climactic transitions, dream sequences
} as const;
```

### 3.2 Use cases
| Token   | Where                                                              |
|---------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|
| whisper | Reveal entry on text (animates → 0 over `DUR.standard`)            |
| soft    | Image entry, image hover-out, secondary imagery                    |
| haze    | Background images, video poster frames, atmospheric layers         |
| veil    | Chapter transitions (out-going scene blurs as it leaves)           |
| fog     | Climactic transitions only — used ≤ 2× per site                    |

### 3.3 Performance constraints
- `backdrop-filter: blur(...)` is **expensive**. Limit to ≤ 1 element per viewport.
- For large blurred surfaces (full-screen), use a **prerendered blurred image asset**, not a runtime filter.
- Always promote blurred elements to compositor: `transform: translateZ(0)` + `will-change: filter` (clear after).
- Disable blur in `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` — replace with opacity.

### 3.4 Forbidden
- ❌ Glassmorphism (frosted card UI). Strictly forbidden.
- ❌ Blurred backgrounds behind text without ≥ 0.6 contrast ratio for the text.
- ❌ Animated blur values per scroll tick. Use scrubbed GSAP timelines or static states.

---

## 4. Shadow Language

The project rejects classical UI shadows (drop shadows, "elevation"). Depth comes from **atmosphere, not drop shadows**.

### 4.1 Allowed shadows
| Token        | Value                                                              | Use                                |
|--------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------|
| `shadow.lift`| `0 1px 0 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.04)`                                        | Hairline separator under sticky nav (rare) |
| `shadow.image`| `0 60px 120px -60px rgba(0,0,0,0.45)`                              | Below large editorial images on light bgs  |
| `shadow.cinematic` | `0 100px 200px -80px rgba(0,0,0,0.6)`                          | Hero image lift (≤ 1× per page)            |

### 4.2 Forbidden
- ❌ Material Design elevation shadows.
- ❌ Multiple stacked shadow layers ("neumorphism").
- ❌ Soft glow / "neon outer glow" shadows.
- ❌ Shadows on text (text-shadow).
- ❌ Shadows on UI controls (buttons, inputs).

---

## 5. Ambient Overlays

Overlays unify and grade scenes. Always sit between background and content.

### 5.1 Types
- **Vignette** — radial gradient darkening edges. Always present in dark chapters, ≥ 8% intensity at corners.
- **Light leak** — soft warm radial bloom (single, off-center). Used in establishing shots.
- **Color grade** — fullscreen `mix-blend-mode: multiply | overlay` solid layer at 4–10% opacity for chapter tone.
- **Scrim** — top/bottom linear gradient for nav/footer legibility on imagery.

### 5.2 Vignette spec (default)
```css
.atmosphere-vignette::before {
  content: ""; position: absolute; inset: 0;
  background: radial-gradient(
    ellipse at center,
    transparent 55%,
    rgba(0,0,0,0.35) 100%
  );
  pointer-events: none;
  z-index: 2;
}
```

### 5.3 Constraints
- Max **2 ambient overlays** per scene (e.g., grain + vignette).
- Overlays must be **declared in the chapter's atmosphere config**, not added ad-hoc.
- Light leaks animate via `EASE.breath`, ≥ 6s cycle, max 8% opacity peak.

---

## 6. Cinematic Darkness

The project's signature dark scenes are not "dark mode UI" — they are **cinematic darkness**.

### 6.1 Rules
- True black (`#000000`) is **forbidden**. Use `#0A0907` (warm black) or `#0B0D10` (cool black) — see `color-system.mdc`.
- Dark scenes always carry **at least one warm light source** (light leak, ambient overlay, glowing image edge).
- Text on dark scenes is never pure white — use `#EDE6D8` (cream) or `#F2EEE5` (paper).
- Dark scenes always include grain at 0.08–0.12 opacity.

### 6.2 Light direction
- All dark scenes have an **implied light source**. Vignettes and light leaks must originate from the same direction in a chapter (e.g., upper-left). Consistency = cinematic believability.

---

## 7. Visual Breathing

The page must breathe — even in stillness, motion is implied.

### 7.1 Breathing elements
- **Grain drift** (always on, ≥ 8s loop).
- **Vignette pulse** (chapter atmosphere only, ±2% intensity, ≥ 12s loop).
- **WebGL ambient shaders** (chapter atmosphere only — see `webgl-system.mdc`).
- **Image micro-zoom** on hero/establishing (`transform: scale(1) → scale(1.02)` over 12–20s).

### 7.2 Constraints
- Maximum **3 breathing elements simultaneously**. More = visually noisy.
- All breathing motion uses `EASE.breath` (sine.inOut).
- All breathing pauses on `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce`.

---

## 8. Texture Logic

Surfaces should suggest material:

| Surface       | Treatment                                                              |
|---------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Page background (light) | Cream tone (`#F2EEE5`) + grain 0.05 + faint vignette          |
| Page background (dark)  | Warm black (`#0A0907`) + grain 0.10 + radial light leak       |
| Image surface           | Subtle grain overlay 0.06 + edge vignette 4%                  |
| Card / panel            | **Forbidden** unless editorial (chapter index card)           |
| Modal                   | **Forbidden** in this project (use full-page transitions)     |

---

## 9. Atmosphere Configuration per Chapter

Each chapter exports an `atmosphere.config.ts`:
```ts
export const atmosphere = {
  background: "warm-black",       // token from color system
  grain: { texture: "1024", opacity: 0.10, drift: true },
  vignette: { intensity: 0.35, origin: "center" },
  lightLeak: { intensity: 0.06, origin: "upper-left", warmth: "warm" },
  blur: { entry: "soft", chapterTransition: "veil" },
  webglAmbient: "fog-noise" | null,
} as const;
```

The `<ChapterAtmosphere>` component reads this config and composes the layers automatically.

---

## 10. Implementation Standards

- All atmosphere primitives live in `components/atmosphere/`:
  - `<Grain />`, `<Vignette />`, `<LightLeak />`, `<Scrim />`, `<AmbientLayer />`.
- Each primitive is `pointer-events: none`, `position: absolute`, `inset: 0`, with `z-index` reserved tokens (`z.atmosphere = 1–9`).
- Atmospheres must be composed inside the chapter shell, not inside content components.
- All atmosphere assets (textures, LUTs) live in `public/textures/` with version suffixes: `grain-512-v2.png`.
- Always preload critical atmosphere textures via `<link rel="preload" as="image">` in the chapter `head` block.

---

## 11. DO / DON'T

### DO
- DO add grain to every scene. Always.
- DO let atmospheric elements breathe at glacial pacing.
- DO compose atmosphere as named layers (grain → light leak → vignette → content).
- DO grade dark scenes with warmth, not coldness.

### DON'T
- DON'T use pure black or pure white as backgrounds.
- DON'T animate atmosphere fast enough that it draws attention.
- DON'T use glassmorphism, neumorphism, or "frosted card" patterns.
- DON'T stack more than 2 ambient overlays.
- DON'T put grain on interactive UI surfaces.
- DON'T use CSS `filter: noise()` or per-pixel random JS.

---

## 12. Cinematic Rationale

- Grain is the difference between a **screen** and a **photograph**. Without it, every image looks digital.
- Vignettes don't darken — they **focus**. The eye is drawn to whatever the corners suppress.
- Soft warmth in dark scenes is the **single most important** rule preventing the project from looking "tech-ey" or cyberpunk.
- Breathing motion at glacial pacing reads as **alive**, not animated. The audience never notices it consciously — that's the point.
